{"type":"message","id":"393013ff","parentId":"d5115e01","timestamp":"2026-06-10T11:05:23.466Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This PowerShell approach is way too slow and resource-heavy for parsing large binary files. Let me take a completely different, much more practical approach.\n\nActually, let me look at this from a different angle. I know from the APK analysis:\n1. WeChat Login: The app uses the standard WeChat OAuth flow with AppID `wxd506e81fe975a813`\n2. For the Mini Program, we can't use the mobile app's AppID - Mini Programs have their own AppID\n\nThe most realistic approach to \"对接野狐围棋\" would be:\n1. In the Mini Program, use `wx.login()` to get a code\n2. Use appid `wx09786c3fb9eac9a4` + Mini Program's secret (which the user would need to provide from WeChat Official Account Platform) to exchange the code\n3. Then try to use the 野狐围棋 WeChat Open Platform AppID (`wxd506e81fe975a813`) and secret (`e9d5f2...`) to interoperate\n\nBut actually, for a Mini Program, there's no direct way to \"log in to 野狐围棋\" from the Mini Program - they're separate WeChat platforms (Open Platform vs Mini Program). \n\nThe user probably wants a simpler architecture:\n1. Mini Program has its own WeChat login (which we already built)\n2. Use the cloud function to store user's openid and create their own user system\n3. The user's account can be linked to 野狐围棋 if needed\n\nOr maybe the user wants to proxy the 野狐围棋 login through their Mini Program backend? Let me look at this more practically.\n\nActually, I think the user is probably asking me to build a complete login flow that:\n1. Uses wx.login() → gets code\n2. Calls the cloud function → gets openid\n3. Uses the openid + the 野狐围棋 WeChat AppID/Secret to create a session\n4. Then checks if the user has a 野狐围棋 account\n\nBut this doesn't really make sense without knowing the actual 野狐围棋 backend URLs.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach to find the API URLs. Instead of extracting from the binary, let me:\n1. Look at the asset bundle files more carefully - some of them might be plain config\n2. Use a proper tool approach\n\nActually, let me try to look at the small data files first - those under 100KB might be config files.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_l7hgAQxw1L3c1xIFLuYH1032","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Kill previous hanging process and try a much simpler approach\n# Let me just use Get-Content -TotalCount on the small data files to see if they're text-based\n$dataDir = \"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\Downloads\\野狐围棋\\assets\\bin\\Data\"\n$smallFiles = Get-ChildItem $dataDir -File | Where-Object { $_.Length -gt 1000 -and $_.Length -lt 50000 } | Sort-Object Length\n\nforeach ($f in $smallFiles) {\n    Write-Host \"=== $($f.Name) ($($f.Length) bytes) ===\"\n    # Try reading first 300 bytes as text\n    $head = Get-Content $f.FullName -TotalCount 3 -Encoding Byte 2>$null\n    if ($head) {\n        $text = [System.Text.Encoding]::ASCII.GetString($head, 0, [Math]::Min($head.Length, 300))\n        Write-Host $text.Substring(0, [Math]::Min(300, $text.Length))\n    }\n    Write-Host \"\"\n}","timeout":30}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":12475,"output":818,"cacheRead":118272,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":131565,"cost":{"input":0.0017465000000000002,"output":0.00022904000000000002,"cacheRead":0.003311616,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.005287156}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781089513921,"responseId":"d0a41450-a2bf-45be-9912-d345a73bb16c"}}
