{"type":"message","id":"0dfd3f91","parentId":"9db872de","timestamp":"2026-06-10T11:51:52.723Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No Android SDK, no emulator, no ADB, no mitmproxy installed. I need to install:\n\n1. **Android SDK + Emulator** - This is heavy (several GB). This might take too long.\n2. **Alternative: Use a lightweight approach** - Instead of a full Android emulator, I can:\n   a. Use **mitmproxy** + **Android device** (if the user has a physical device)\n   b. Or use a lightweight Android emulator like **LDPlayer** or **MEmu**\n   c. Or use **Android Studio's command line tools** to create an emulator\n\nActually, the simplest approach for network capture would be:\n1. Install **mitmproxy** (Python-based, lightweight)\n2. Install **Android SDK command-line tools** (much smaller than full Android Studio)\n3. Create an AVD (Android Virtual Device) using the command line tools\n4. Install the APK\n5. Set up mitmproxy as a proxy on the device\n6. Capture the traffic\n\nBut actually, this might be easier if I use:\n1. **mitmproxy** on the host\n2. Connect a real device via USB debug mode (if available)\n\nLet me check if Python is available first, since mitmproxy needs it. And let me check if there's any Android device connected.\n\nActually, let me take a more pragmatic approach. Installing a full Android emulator and SDK takes a long time. Let me try:\n\n1. Install mitmproxy (requires Python)\n2. Use it with an actual Android device connected via USB\n3. Or use a cloud Android device service\n\nLet me first check what's available.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_RenMUmOwvLaFrl0E2Ao72693","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check Python and pip\npython --version 2>&1\npip --version 2>&1\nWrite-Host \"---\"\n# Check for any connected Android device\nadb devices 2>&1\nWrite-Host \"---\"\n# Check winget for Android emulators\nwinget search \"android\" 2>&1 | Select-Object -F