{"type":"message","id":"f1db824d","parentId":"4eb2467f","timestamp":"2026-06-10T11:58:42.906Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"GitHub is timing out. This means we can't download external tools. Let me take a completely different approach.\n\nSince we can't download tools from GitHub and the system CA store is read-only, I need to find another way. Let me think about what alternatives I have:\n\n1. **Use a proxy app on the emulator itself** - Since we have root and ADB, I can push a static binary proxy like `mitmproxy` (as a Python package deployed directly)\n   \n2. **Use the built-in MuMu proxy settings** - MuMu emulator might have a proxy setting we can use\n\n3. **Use `iptables` on the emulator to redirect traffic** - Since it's rooted, I can use iptables to redirect all HTTP/HTTPS traffic through the host\n\n4. **Use a simpler approach - just run the app and look at the debug logs** - Unity apps often log network URLs in debug output\n\n5. **Try to capture the PCAP using adb shell** - Push a static binary\n\nLet me try option 3 - this is the most promising:\n- Run mitmproxy on the host (already installed)\n- Use iptables on the emulator to redirect port 80/443 to host's proxy\n- The cert is already in /data/misc/user/0/cacerts-added/\n- Run the app and capture traffic\n\nActually, for option 3 to work with HTTPS, I need the CA cert to be trusted. But on Android 12, user-added CAs aren't trusted by default. However, since this is an emulator running a Unity game (which typically targets an older API level or uses its own SSL handling), there might be a chance.\n\nActually, let me try a MUCH simpler approach. Unity games on Android often use `UnityWebRequest` which uses the system's SSL trust store. For apps targeting API < 24 (Android 6), user certs ARE trusted. But for apps targeting API 24+, user certs are NOT trusted.\n\nHowever, there's a trick: I can use `adb shell settings put global development_settings_enabled 1` and then install the cert through the security settings manually. Let me try opening the cert installer on the emulator and navigating through it.\n\nOr better yet - let me try the most direct approach: set up a transparent proxy using iptables + mitmproxy.\n\nActually, let me try the simplest thing first: configure the WiFi proxy on the emulator to point to our host's mitmproxy and see if it works.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"GitHub 连不上。我换个思路——用模拟器的 iptables 把所有流量重定向到本机 mitmproxy。"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_tky9liOLgu9YtdaGWfRM8291","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"$adb = \"C:\\Program Files\\Unity\\Hub\\Editor\\2020.3.49f1\\Editor\\Data\\PlaybackEngines\\AndroidPlayer\\SDK\\platform-tools\\adb.exe\"\n$pythonDir = \"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\Scripts\"\n$env:Path = \"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312;$pythonDir;$env:Path\"\n\n# Step 1: Start mitmproxy in transparent mode on the host\n# First, get the host IP that the emulator can reach\n$hostIP = \"10.0.2.2\"  # This is the standard gateway for Android emulators\nWrite-Host \"Host IP (emulator gateway): $hostIP\"\n\n# Step 2: Start mitmproxy in background\nWrite-Host \"Starting mitmweb on port 8080...\"\n$env:PYTHONUNBUFFERED = \"1\"\n$process = Start-Process -NoNewWindow -FilePath \"mitmweb\" -ArgumentList \"--web-port 8081 --listen-port 8080 --set block_global=false\" -PassThru\nStart-Sleep 3\n\n# Check if it's running\nGet-Process -Name \"python*\" | Select-Object Id, ProcessName\n# Check the port\nnetstat -an | findstr \"8080\" 2>&1 | Select-Object -First 3","timeout":20}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":67,"output":940,"cacheRead":190080,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":191087,"cost":{"input":0.00000938,"output":0.0002632,"cacheRead":0.00532224,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0055948199999999995}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781092