{"type":"message","id":"35086390","parentId":"3898511e","timestamp":"2026-06-10T12:01:20.688Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I found very important info! Let me analyze the connection data:\n\nFrom `/proc/net/tcp`:\n- `D3FE70C1:01BB` → IP decoded: D3=211, FE=254, 70=112, C1=193 → **193.112.254.211** (Wait, that's wrong - let me recalculate)\n  \n  Actually for the hex IP `D3FE70C1`:\n  - D3 = 211\n  - FE = 254  \n  - 70 = 112\n  - C1 = 193 (wait, C1=193? No, C1 is 193 in hex but this is IP format... \n  \n  Actually in /proc/net/tcp, IP is stored as 4 bytes in network byte order. But the hex in /proc/net/tcp is stored as little-endian hex.\n  \n  `D3 FE 70 C1` as little-endian hex represents... let me think.\n  \n  The format is: the hex number represents the IP in network byte order (big endian). So `D3FE70C1` = 211.254.112.193 in network byte order.\n  \n  Let me recalculate: 0xD3 = 211, 0xFE = 254, 0x70 = 112, 0xC1 = 193\n  So the IP is: **193.112.254.211** (wait, C1 is 193)\n\n  Actually no. In `/proc/net/tcp`, the IP is stored as a 32-bit number in **network byte order** (big-endian). So `D3 FE 70 C1` = 211.254.112.193. Let me just use a calculator.\n\nLet me use Python to decode these hex IPs properly.\n\nFrom tcp6:\n- `2C3165B4:01BB` → 44.49.101.180:443?\n  Actually for tcp6, the IP is in IPv4-mapped IPv6 format. `0000000000000000FFFF00000F02000A` → the last 4 bytes `0F02000A` = 10.0.2.15 (emulator IP).\n  And `2C3165B4:01BB` → 44.49.101.180:443 (port 443 = 0x01BB)\n\nWait, `2C3165B4`: 2C=44, 31=49, 65=101, B4=180 → so the IP is in network byte order: 44.49.101.180... Actually wait, these are in hex, and in `/proc/net` the format is network byte order.\n\nHmm, let me just use Python to decode these.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the connections:\n- `2C3165B4:01BB` - This is on port 443 (HTTPS)\n- `927AEC73:01BB` - Another HTTPS connection\n\nLet me decode these with Python.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_1psRNuJWEyjbq6vhqyBN3364","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Decode IP addresses from /proc/net/tcp format using Python\npython -c \"\nimport socket, struct\n\n# From tcp connections\nhex_ips = {\n    'D3FE70C1': 'app connection 1',\n    '2C3165B4': 'tcp6 conn 1',\n    '927AEC73': 'tcp6 conn 2',\n}\n\nfor hex_str, desc in hex_ips.items():\n    # Convert hex string to bytes (network byte order = big endian in /proc/net)\n    ip_bytes = bytes.fromhex(hex_str)\n    # For /proc/net/tcp, the format is 4 bytes in network byte order\n    # But wait - /proc/net/tcp stores the address as a 32-bit LE number\n    # So D3FE70C1 → C1,70,FE,D3 when read as LE\n    ip_int = int(hex_str, 16)\n    # The /proc/net/tcp format is actually just the raw 4 bytes in hex\n    # Just convert it directly\n    b1 = (ip_int >> 24) & 0xFF\n    b2 = (ip_int >> 16) & 0xFF\n    b3 = (ip_int >> 8) & 0xFF\n    b4 = ip_int & 0xFF\n    print(f'{hex_str} ({desc}): {b1}.{b2}.{b3}.{b4}')\n\" 2>&1","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":1420,"output":1025,"cacheRead":204032,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":206477,"cost":{"input":0.0001988,"output":0.00028700000000000004,"cacheRead":0.005712895999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.006198695999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781092867334,"responseId":"adaff6b7-430e-4365-92f7-e6ed9317571c"}}
