{"type":"message","id":"e9c04a43","parentId":"0bd4e432","timestamp":"2026-06-10T13:12:51.064Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Git remote works via SSH with the current key (yyzypublic). No credentials are stored in the git config.\n\nSince I can't easily access the GitLab API to check lishengfei's permissions, let me try a different approach. Let me check if there are any cached responses or branch protections that might indicate who has write access.\n\nBut actually, the most practical way is to check the file permissions via GitLab's web interface, or to try to push a test commit as \"lishengfei\".\n\nWait - I just had an idea. I can use the git `ls-remote` with a specific SSH key to test user access. But I don't have lishengfei's key.\n\nLet me try one more thing - check if the GitLab API works with a `sudo` query or if there's any way to get the project's member list via git commands.\n\nActually, there's a very practical approach I haven't tried yet. GitLab has a built-in feature where you can check file permissions using `git annex` or `git fsck`. But that's not what I need.\n\nLet me think about this from a GitLab admin perspective:\n1. GitLab projects have Maintainer, Developer, Reporter, Guest roles\n2. The project URL is `yyzy/develop_client/nightoffullmoon`\n3. The namespace `yyzy` is likely a group\n4. lishengfei's username is likely `lishengfei`\n\nFor checking permissions, I need either:\n- GitLab admin access (I don't have)\n- An API token with `read_api` scope (I don't have)\n- Web UI access to the project members page (I don't have)\n\nSince I can't use the API, let me try one last approach - check if the GitLab server has a public project membership API, or check if there's an impersonation token available.\n\nActually, let me ask - the current SSH key works for yyzypublic. In many GitLab setups, project members can be queried using a Personal Access Token. Let me check if I can create one via the GitLab API using the current SSH session for auth.\n\nActually no - creating a PAT via API also requires authentication.\n\nLet me just try the GitLab API with a simple URL pattern that might work for self-hosted instances.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_XhIL5WGICWQxAyzchZw22818","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Let me try several API endpoints that might be accessible\n$baseUrl = \"https://git.devcloud.ztgame.com/api/v4\"\n\n$endpoints = @(\n    \"/projects?search=nightoffullmoon&per_page=5\",\n    \"/projects/yyzy%2Fdevelop_client%2Fnightoffullmoon\",\n    \"/users?search=lishengfei\",\n    \"/groups/yyzy/members\",\n    \"/projects/yyzy%2Fdevelop_client%2Fnightoffullmoon/members\",\n    \"/projects/yyzy%2Fdevelop_client%2Fnightoffullmoon/members/all\"\n)\n\nforeach ($ep in $endpoints) {\n    try {\n        $url = \"$baseUrl$ep\"\n        $result = Invoke-WebRequest -Uri $url -UseBasicParsing -TimeoutSec 5\n        if ($result.StatusCode -eq 200) {\n            Write-Host \"✅ $ep - $($result.StatusCode)\"\n            $data = $result.Content | ConvertFrom-Json\n            \n            if ($data -is [Array]) {\n                $data | Select-Object id, username, name, access_level, state | Format-Table -AutoSize\n            } elseif ($data.name) {\n                Write-Host \"  Project: $($data.name), Visibility: $($data.visibility)\"\n            } else {\n                Write-Host \"  $($result.Content.Substring(0, [Math]::Min(200, $result.Content.Length)))\"\n            }\n        } else {\n            Write-Host \"❌ $ep - $($result.StatusCode)\"\n        }\n    } catch {\n        $code = $_.Exception.Response.StatusCode.value__\n        $msg = $_.Exception.Message\n        Write-Host \"❌ $ep - HTTP $code ($msg)\"\n    }\n}","timeout":30}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":724,"output":932,"cacheRead":256384,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":258040,"cost":{